The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Excise cut fuels April car sales
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Excise cut fuels April car sales
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                                          
	New Delhi, May 8: The first month of the new fiscal brought cheers to the autombile industry, thanks to a cut in excise duty on small cars and two - and three-wheelers.        
	While passenger cars registered a sales growth of 17.15 per cent, motorcycles grew 8.31 per cent in April.        
	According to data released by the Society of Indian Automobile Manufacturers, passenger cars clocked sales of 98,740 units during the month against 84,283 units in the same month a year ago.        
	Yes, the excise cuts have definitely brought about improvement. One month results are not a great indicator, while it is a positive move for sure, said Jnaneswar Sen, senior general manager of Honda Siel Cars India.         
	Domestic vehicle sales in April stood at 8,06,238 units against 7,34,103 in the same month last year, a growth rateof 9.83 per cent.        
	In passenger cars, Maruti Suzuki India reported a 22.30 per cent rise in sales at 51,766 units compared with 42,326 in the corresponding month of the previous year.        
	Hyundai Motors India sold 21,492 units during the month against 15,697 units last year, an increase of 36.92 per cent.        
	Tata Motors, however, reported a decline of 17.10 per cent at 11,193 units compared with 13,502 in the same month of the previous year.        
	General Motors India posted a 21.65 per cent jump in sales with its hatchback Spark putting up a good show. The companys overall sales stood at 3,411 units compared with 2,804 units last year.        
	Motorcycles reported sales of 5,01,592 units in April against 4,63,091 units in the year-ago month.        
	Hero Honda Motors sold 2,76,580 bikes compared with 2,55,408 units in the same period last year, up 8.29 per cent.        
	Rival Bajaj Auto recorded an increase of 9.19 per cent at 1,38,117 units against 1,26,494 last year. TVS Motor sales were up 2.35 per cent at 49,186 units compared with 48,058 units in the same month last year.        
	Total two-wheeler sales in April grew 8 per cent to 6,16,038 units from 5,70,381 units in the same month last year, said the industry body.        
	In the scooter segment, total sales witnessed an 11.93 per cent increase at 81,002 units against 72,369 units.        
	Scooter market leader Honda Motorcycle amp; Scooter India, however, registered sales of 47,396 units compared with 48,488 units, down 2.25 per cent. Hero Honda Motors pushed its sales over four-fold at 5,832 units from 1,291 units in the same month last year.                                                                                                                                     
